segments.text: We were talking about football and that game in Austin and so forth.
What athletic events do you remember most in those first three years?
Well, of course, that game was quite important.
The game we beat the University of Texas here in 1939 was when we cinched the championship.
because we were tied.
We were zero, I think, in the first play.
In the second, we had a hideout play, and Herb Smith caught a pass for a touchdown.
We beat them 21 to nothing.
As far as you know, did athletes go to class and graduate then pretty well?
I really can't say particularly what they did.
Of course, most of them at that time, they better have gone through and
and get their commissions and go on.
I think that's what most of them did.
Were there any of those football players that you all respected highly?
Of course, Kimbrough was outstanding, of course, I guess.
He was a fine fellow.
He even caught a ride with him one time in this thing.
He had his own car and whatnot.
What was your impression of him?
Well, I think he was a fine fellow, really was.
In fact, I think that whole team was pretty good.
I had Buster Keaton, who was a junior yell leader then, and was quite close to him, much more so than now.
He said, oh, Marshall Robnett, who was a guard, he said that what old Robnett would do, first play from scrimmage, he'd urinate all over himself.
He was really rough and this sort of thing.
That's about all of them.
I really can't say more than that.
What about the core leadership in terms of the commandant and the advisors?
Who were they then?
Well, of course, Colonel Welty was our advisor for the Signal Corps.
Colonel Davis, he was an Aggie, and he was kind of permanent.
He wasn't a PMS&T.
PMS&T, of course, was on active duty, and they sent him here for several years.
And, of course, one of them,
That was the PMS&T wound up in Corregidor.
I really can't say more than that.
Our own Lieutenant Lerner, I imagine he was a signal coordinator sort of for it.
We got acquainted with the enlisted men, too.
We took code.
So we had an enlisted man that teaches Mars code in the Bolton Hall.
And then Sergeant Snyder
was also with the Signal Corps, and when the war came on, they gave him a commission.
But that's about all I can say about them.
Did you know Colonel Andy?
Well, no, Colonel Andy was the track coach.
So he was not the commandant then?
No.
Let's see, we mentioned Muster.
Final review.
Was there final review held in those days?
Oh, sure.
Where?
On where they have final reviews now, in front of the Memorial Student Center.
At that time, those were campus houses along there.
But for final review, just like it is now, you marched around once with the seniors, and then you marched again without the seniors.
The new seniors took over.
They didn't go home and put their boots on, though, or anything like that.
And it just went right through.
I remember one time my freshman year standing so straight.
I don't know if it was the final review of Mother's Day or something.
Anyway, I fainted.
Because when you stand straight and you don't wiggle your toes, the next thing I knew I was on the ground.
As the war progressed, as
Life gets more serious.
Did the freshman hazing here change?
Well, I think it let up quite a bit.
I feel sure it must have because we realized the seriousness of it.
As I say, when I was a company commander, I had them cut it out.
And you lived all of those pre-war years in what is now the Corps?
I lived in Dorm 1, but what happened?
In the summer of 40, no, let's see, the fall of 42, they brought in a lot of Navy men for code practice and for repair.
So all 12 dormitories were taken over by them, and we doubled up.
in Mitchell Hall, and all those, of course, we got much smaller by then.
We put three in a room.
You'd have a bunk three high.
So we lived in Mitchell Hall that fall.
Do you remember any changes in any curriculum, any courses that seemed to be war-related?
No, not really.
I kind of think we eliminated final exams, I'm not sure, because of the speed-up.
Mm-hmm.
And so at night, did you and your buddies listen to the war news regularly?
No, I don't remember doing that.
No, I really don't.
And you didn't take a daily paper.
Nobody took a newspaper.
I think we did kind of, yeah.
We kept up with it, but I don't know that we dwelt on it a lot.
And as the war is going on, how often did you go home to Dallas?
Well, of course we had gas rationing.
So we went, I'd say, two or three times a semester.
And as I say, I went home that fall
and got the car so I could bring my date back and other people and that sort of thing.
And also you had to drive at 35 or 40 miles an hour.
Now, did you keep the car down here then?
No, I didn't.
I kept it down just for that couple of weeks.
No, no.
And your microphone fell down.
Yeah.
And of course you got gas rationing stamps and this sort of thing.
Let's see.
I don't know what I'm going to do.
I'm going to put that microphone right there and see if I can keep it.
Yeah.
All right.
You go away to the war and then come back when?
I came back the fall of 46.
No, this is what happened after the war was over.
You had a points system, and you had to get so many points you were entitled to get out.
Well, I didn't go overseas, so I didn't get as many points as one that did go overseas, so many of them are already coming back for the summer semester and even for the spring semester of 46.
I had 40 hours to go.
It took three semesters, though, because of the sequence of courses that I needed to take.
What was different about your attitude from being a student in 46 than it ever was?
I wanted to get through school and get out and go to work.
What had you learned during the war that helped you in your courses?
Oh, I just got a maturity.
I did get to be a cryptographic officer.
I did study teletype, go through maintenance school, and then also through the cryptographic machines.
So I had more of an idea of applications and this sort of thing.
But I mainly wanted to get through and get out and get a job.
Now, you said you were married and had a youngster.
I met my wife at the University of Delaware.
And I took her to her junior prom, but that first date I said, I just met the girl I'm going to marry.
So after I got out of OCS and she graduated, we got married.
And we had one child in the service, and the second one was born here while I was back in school.
And you all lived in, when you came here, you lived where?
The what?
When you came here with your wife and child, where did you all live?
Oh, we...
She lived with my parents in Dallas until College View Apartments opened, so I lived in the dormitory.
Describe life in College View.
In College View?
Well, my wife is about the only one that couldn't drive a car.
She was a Yankee.
But all these Texas girls, they knew how to drive and everything.
And, of course, we were all veterans, and they had different stories about pregnancy and this sort of thing.
And we played baseball.
We had baseball teams.
And I had a bicycle.
I didn't have a car.
And A&P in Bryan was the closest place for a supermarket.
So I'd ride that bicycle all the way into Bryan to pick up our groceries and this sort of thing.
And it was just one big happy family.
All of us more or less had children.
And they had a great time together.
I think it was a real way for our oldest daughter to mature, to get with these older boys.
Were you a better student?
Oh, definitely.
Oh, sure, definitely.
Did your grades show it?
Yeah, pretty well.
At that time, you could exempt final exams if you had good enough grades.
I was taking an M.E.
course, and I was going to exempt, and
So the prof came in and said, well, everybody's going to have to take the final.
Somebody stole my grade book.
Well, I was going to get out.
But then after a while, he came back and says, well, my grade book came back.
So I got out.
And there was a football player who stole that grade book.
So he got it back.
Ed Holdridge told me that story.
Now, you were here how long after the war?
Well, I was here a full year.
A full year.
And what did you think you were preparing yourself for?
What kind of career did you?
Well, of course, being an elected engineer, I could have gone with, say, GE or Westinghouse or Alachammer's or a utility or with a telephone company.
Well, my father worked for Graybar Electric Company in Dallas, and so the branch manager in Houston convinced me to go with them, which I did, worked for them for nine years.
And one of the propositions was GE would take me and send me through the test course
where I would learn GE equipment so that when I went with Graybar, I would be able to sell the stuff better.
So anyway, we moved to Houston after graduation.
And so at that point, you weren't thinking about an academic career?
Nobody else was thinking of one for me either.
When I finally got one and I told my daughter that I was going to teach at A&M, she says, Daddy, you're not smart enough to teach.
But after I was in Houston for six years and got transferred to Baton Rouge and then transferred back over.
And I was living here, traveling the territory when I got a chance to teach.
My next door neighbor was Frank Vandiver in Baton Rouge for one summer.
Yeah, he was there taught for the summer.
He was down at Tulane at the time, and then he came over to Rice, and that's when he was your prof, wasn't he?
I'm his first doctoral student.
At Rice, yeah.
And, of course, we knew Susie, his first wife.
We went by and visited them and all that.
Marvelous person.
Did you go to Mustard that senior year when you came back?
No, definitely.
Did it seem different to you after the war?
Okay.
It was in front of what was the administration building.
It was there that day, and that's where we had our muster.
It was an afternoon meeting.
Did things on the campus seem more serious in 46, 47?
Oh, I think so.
We were all predominantly veterans.
And we wanted to get in and get out.
And I'm assuming that hazing wasn't very prevalent then.
No.
What did all of these young wives do?
Well, they were mostly pregnant.
They didn't work, though, at all.
I mean, we got, I guess, $90 a month plus all of our tuition, and that was about it.
Did the GI Bill pretty well pay your way?
Well, yep, I think pretty well.
They also paid all the tuition costs and all the books and this sort of thing.
But then it wasn't $90 a month.
Where did you and your wife get your furnishings for that College View?
Oh, it was furnished.
Oh, it was.
It had just the normal cots, and it had, I think, a double bed in the bedroom and bunk beds.
How did y'all get here?
How did you arrive in College Station?
How did we arrive?
Well, we just went up to Dallas on the train and drove her back with what belongings we had.
We had, I guess, a baby bed we put her in and a little washing machine and a few other things, and that was it.
Let's see, and you're not in the Corps as a veteran.
And were there some faculty members that were really important to you as you look back now that you had in that post-war year?
I really can't say there were any at all.
If you could, throughout all of your years at A&M,
If you could recall them to life and thank them personally, to which faculty members do you feel the most grateful?
Well, of course, the electrical engineering class, Foyker.
Which ones?
Well, Foyker I thought was nice, and Dillingham, Norman Road, and R.P.
Ward.
I thought the liberal arts,
teachers were all very good, the English and of course the math profs and this sort of thing.
I had Luther way back when I was a freshman in trigonometry.
And of course one fellow I'm fond of is Alphabet Thompson, J. George H. Thompson.
And we had him in kinematics drawing.
This is before the war.
And so he was talking about he went to Penn State and what it cost him on the weekend to have a date.
And my roommate said, well, I went up to TSCW and back for the weekend and I spent 25 cents.
Well, he couldn't imagine that because he hitchhiked and they fed him up there and that sort of thing.
I know I've heard many people refer to Dr. Thompson with gratitude.
Oh, yeah.
What were his trademarks?
What did he do that was special?
Oh, I don't know.
He was just genuinely interested in me.
I know when I was teaching, I had a guy taking a course from me, and he questioned how I had graded his papers.
And I didn't know if he could show me where he got it from, okay.
And so he didn't say any more.
And a little while he came back, and he confessed that he had cheated.
And the way, what he happened, so he, George noticed that he was just kind of upset or something, didn't know what to do.
He finally asked him, what's wrong?
And he told him.
And George says, well, you can do two things, not do anything, or you can go back and tell me.
But you must remember, he can kick you out of school because of that.
So anyway, he came back and confessed and told me the story and this sort of thing.
But of course, I wasn't going to do anything about it.
Did you give him any advice then?
Who, that young man?
Yes.
No, not really.
I can't remember giving him any advice.
What else can you say?
Let me put in the notes here then, one that I had like that.
This was about March.
I was in my office talking to my grader, and a sophomore came, and he said, I need to talk to you.
I said, well, come back in a few minutes because I'm busy right now.
He came back about a half hour later.
And he closed the door behind me, which is a little bit of a surprise.
And he sat down, and he had a Bible in his lap, which was not common for a core sophomore.
And I said, can I help you?
And he said, yes, sir, I wanted to tell you.
I cheated on your final exam last semester.
I said, oh, really?
Tell me about it.
Well, he said it was in the big section, and four of us decided we'd each study one-fourth of the material, and then we'd pass the answers back and forth.
Because we set up on the back row.
Yeah.
And because he said, we don't think anybody else would have done that.
I said, oh, I bet you're right.
I bet nobody else has ever tried to pass that.
And I asked him what his average was before the final, and he said 75.
I said, what does the final count?
He said one-fourth.
And I said, how high would you have had to make on the final to
to have raised the 75 to a B.
And how low could you have made and not pull the 75 down to a C?
And he realized, oh.
And I said, why are you telling me this?
And he said, well, sir, I'm a Baptist.
And last night at BSU, we had a missionary who gave us a Bible study and said, if you have sinned against God, get out on your knees tonight.
And if you sinned against one of your fellow men, go to that person and confess the sin.
And he said, that's why I'm here.
I said, you didn't hurt me.
I said, you hurt yourself.
And he thought I had the authority to kick him out of school.
And I said, if I give you an F in this course, he said, when I get home, my dad's going to beat the hell out of me.
And he said, we're farmers, so I'll just be farming.
And I said, what have you learned from this?
And he said, I'll never, never, never do this again.
Yeah.
And I said, okay, I'll make a deal with you.
As of this moment, I will forget your name, and I may tell this story many times, but I will never, ever, ever do it.
Yeah.
If you will promise me that you'll never, ever again do it.
Yeah.
And he shook my hand and walked out, and I've always hoped that at some point...
This young man, because this is 30, 35 years ago, woke up to me.
I'd like to know if he remembers that.
Yeah, I bet he did.
You know he did.
All right, you said we were getting people to whom you feel grateful that had a lifetime effect on you.
And you mentioned George Thompson last.
Some others?
Were there any people that just gave you advice?
Well, of course, my fellow faculty members, some of them were very helpful to me to get started in this sort of thing, like John Dennison and, of course, Dillingham.
When he left, I took over his office in this sort of thing.
And Rode, he wanted me to change out, but I didn't, you know, to change and go into education.
This is when I was teaching, but I decided I didn't want to do that.
I tried it a little bit.

Of course, one of the students I like is one that he came into my office to advise, and I was at my desk, and I was kind of working, and he said, well, you know, would you stop and pay attention to me?
And I realized I've got to give him attention, so my desk and then a table, and after that I always turned away from my desk and sat there and gave him my attention.
I think something as little as that, yeah.
As you, do you remember commencement, your undergraduate commencement?
We didn't have one because this was August, so they didn't have one.
Dr. Williams directed me to plan the first August commencement.
Really?
Yeah.
He'd gotten two letters from two different mothers who had said, this is not fair.
Our child graduated.
He's graduating this summer and got to wait until December.
They've got a job a long way away.
What do you think?
And I said, I think this is a mandate.
And he said, do you think anybody will show up?
Yeah.
We've proven how much they'll show up.
Yeah.
So how well prepared did you feel you were when you graduated?
How well prepared did you think A&M had been?
Well, I was very much an average student, and I really feel like I was, a good place that I went was when I went in more into sales.
I really don't, I really, I was exposed to all of it, but I really knew that I couldn't get into something highly technical.
While I was in the service room, while I was in research in Arlington, Virginia,
after the war was over, but I really, I couldn't do much then originally, this sort of thing.
So I guess I'm not a typical graduate.
And I, wonderful the way I've turned out.
I mean, how I fell into this job here and how I felt that I really did a good job with the students and this sort of thing.
Of course, the recognition I got and
Did A&M help you get that first job?
No, uh-uh.
At that time, of course, you had all these different companies coming in and interviewing, and they had nothing to do with it.

No, and as I say, because the guy I was going to work for had worked with my father and so forth, and he wanted me, they were hiring a lot of double E's then, but as it turned out, we couldn't make much use of it, and I was traveling, and I really wasn't, and I had a chance,
I talked to Randy Mattson.
I don't know, I guess you'd, Walt Mattson.
You remember him?
Okay.
But anyway, I talked to him that spring because they had taken some of my accounts away from me, the telephone companies, incidentally.
And I said, well, I'm not using my engineering.
And I talked to him.
He says, well, no, you just got your BS.
And on Wednesday before classes in September, he says, go around and see MC Hughes.
He might have a job for you.
I went over to see him, and they hired me at lunchtime.
I called Houston and went down and resigned on Friday and helped with registration on Saturday.
That first job out of A&M, what was the pay?
Do you remember?
$190 a month, and they were scraping pretty good.
Let's see.
Now let's see.
Let's see.
Did you buy an Aggie ring?
I have an Aggie ring.
How much did it cost, do you remember?
Oh, back in those days, about $25.
And was the ritual the same then as now, that almost everybody bought a ring?
Oh, very definitely.
In fact, some guys would get somebody else to buy a ring and give it to them.
That's how important it was.
All right.
Let's see, one that I see I missed here, Aggie Bonfire.
Was there a bonfire your freshman year?
Oh yeah, there was always a bonfire.
Where was it?
It was out on the drill field.
And there was nothing much at all to it.
You know, this is awful what they do now, but we got the railroads to bring in stuff for us.
And it was trash then, wasn't it?
About all it was.
And we'd go and cut down a few trees.
Let's see, I've heard Mr.
Rudder talk about trying to shoot out that light bulb up on top of the- I've heard that too.
Was that done?
No, no, I don't think so.
Okay.
Let's see, we've already talked about hard lickers.
Okay, now let's, you came as a faculty member in what year?
It'd be the fall of 56th.
And this is the last one I'm going to ask of dollars and cents.
Do you remember what the pay was when you started?
$500 a month, I think.
Maybe $550, I don't know.
And what was your title?
Well, I was an instructor.
And what were your first duties?
What was my what?
First duty.
What were you assigned to teach?
Oh, okay.
First term sophomore course.
And then labs, and a 307 course, which is for the mechanical engineers, with the labs.
And for a number of years, we had the labs as well as the theory, which was great, because this is really where you got acquainted with them.
So that was my first semester.
Nineteen contact hours.
In double E or in double E?
In double E. Oh, yeah, I stayed in double E. About how many were there, how many faculty in the department field?
Oh, eight or nine, I guess.
And you all were housed, where were you all housed?
Oh, in Bolton Hall.
In Bolton.
And how would you compare the students that you had that first year with the students that were here when you arrived?
Were they better prepared than y'all were?
Oh, I think that what was really nice when I came back is you had Corps and you had veterans.
The veterans were very much dedicated.
And so as a result, the Corps was too.
They were good students.
Because these were Korean War veterans.
These would have been Korean War veterans in the mid-50s.
Oh yeah, Korean War.
And so...
A day for you as a faculty member began at about what time and when did a day?
Oh, 8 o'clock till 5.
Yeah, the collabs would go on to 5. Who was the department head?
M.C.
Hughes.
Describe him as a...
They called him Tubby.
Tubby Hughes, he was a big heavy man, and he had gone through the test course, that is, with GE and this sort of thing, and...
I guess he came on back fairly soon after that and was the department head for a number of years.
Who was the dean of engineering?
Gilchrist.
And the dean of the faculty was Bolton.
And the president, Walton.
Oh, yeah.
And in what manner did Professor Hughes lead the department?
Was he authoritarian?
Was he democratic?
Oh, I think he was very fair and everything.
He certainly was fair to me.
And I think he just was a very regular type of department head.
How, all right, then we're doing a broad survey now of all your years.
How did the Department of Engineering attempt to stay up to date with what it offered?
Well, of course, prior to up to World War II,
through the war, you still, as we were concerned, in power, not much on electronics.
And they were all teaching very much traditional courses, mechanical, civil, chemical, and this sort of thing.
The chemical engineering department was pretty new.
It was part of the chemistry department until about World War II.
And so it was a very stable type of curriculum.
But what about after the war?
How did...
Well, of course, once the transistor came in and they started doing this sort of thing, then the whole picture changed.
And then, of course, all the field theory and much more emphasis on electronics, on communications, such as that.
And so gradually it downplayed the
the power because this is not where most of the students go anymore.
Was there any program to give you as a new faculty member any orientation?
You and your wife?
Not a bit.
But my wife's very personal and she already knew a lot of the faculty and this sort of thing.
Where did y'all live?
We lived on 103 Dexter.
This is the last block before you
